Title: Frankenstein
Credit: Written by
Author: Mary Wollstonecraft Shelley
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 7/20/2026
Notes: Period live-action; cold northern palette; candlelight and ice. Cast: ROBERT WALTON (28, lean English explorer, dark hair, weathered, furs and naval coat); MARGARET SAVILLE (his sister, England, letters only); LIEUTENANT WILLOUGHBY (English, bold, professional); MASTER FLETCHER (gentle, mild, uneducated seaman); VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN (European—emaciated when found, frostbitten, wild melancholy eyes; dark-haired Genevese gentleman); ALPHONSE FRANKENSTEIN (fifty-plus, upright, grave kind face); CAROLINE FRANKENSTEIN (fair, resolute, tender); ELIZABETH LAVENZA (golden hair, blue eyes, celestial features); HENRY CLERVAL (open face, bright fancy); ERNEST FRANKENSTEIN (youth, active); WILLIAM FRANKENSTEIN (small child, blue eyes, curling hair); JUSTINE MORITZ (young, pretty, gentle, frank); M. KREMPE (repulsive physiognomy, sharp manners); M. WALDMAN (kind, silvered, gentle); THE CREATURE (eight feet, yellowed skin over taut muscle, lustrous black hair, watery eyes, black lips, gigantic stature, rough scavenged garments); DE LACEY (blind, white-haired, dignified in poverty); FELIX DE LACEY (lean, dark-eyed, sorrow-etched); AGATHA DE LACEY (young, gentle, worn hands); SAFIE (dark-eyed, graceful Arabian); OFFICER MERLE (Geneva court officer); MR. KIRWIN (Irish magistrate).

===

EXT. STREETS OF ST. PETERSBURGH - DAY

Late 18th century. Snow packed hard underfoot. A cold northern breeze cuts the air.

ROBERT WALTON, twenty-eight, lean and bright-eyed, walks in heavy furs. The wind strikes his cheeks. He closes his eyes a moment, smiling, braced and delighted.

He looks north, as if he can already see the pole.

INT. WALTON'S LODGING - ST. PETERSBURGH - NIGHT

A plain rented room. Candle. Ink. Paper.

Walton writes with quick, eager strokes. He speaks the letter as he forms it—half to the page, half to the sister he imagines.

ROBERT WALTON
You will rejoice to hear that no disaster has accompanied the commencement of an enterprise which you have regarded with such evil forebodings. I arrived here yesterday, and my first task is to assure my dear sister of my welfare.

He pauses, touches the cold window glass. Frost ferns the pane.

ROBERT WALTON
I am already far north of London, and as I walk in the streets of Petersburgh, I feel a cold northern breeze play upon my cheeks, which braces my nerves and fills me with delight. Do you understand this feeling?

EXT. STREETS OF ST. PETERSBURGH - DAY

Walton again in the wind—daydreaming as he walks.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
This breeze, which has travelled from the regions towards which I am advancing, gives me a foretaste of those icy climes. I try in vain to be persuaded that the pole is the seat of frost and desolation; it ever presents itself to my imagination as the region of beauty and delight.

His eyes shine.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
There, Margaret, the sun is for ever visible. What may not be expected in a country of eternal light? I may there discover the wondrous power which attracts the needle—tread a land never before imprinted by the foot of man.

INT. WALTON'S LODGING - ST. PETERSBURGH - NIGHT

Walton writes on, fervor rising.

ROBERT WALTON
These are my enticements, and they are sufficient to conquer all fear of danger or death. Nothing contributes so much to tranquillise the mind as a steady purpose—a point on which the soul may fix its intellectual eye.

He sits back. Memory takes him.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
This expedition has been the favourite dream of my early years.

EXT. ENGLISH COUNTRYSIDE - DAY - FLASHBACK

A boy among a few worn volumes. Uncle Thomas’s library: accounts of voyages, nothing else.

Young Walton reads as if starving.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
A history of all the voyages made for purposes of discovery composed the whole of our good Uncle Thomas’ library. My education was neglected, yet I was passionately fond of reading. My father’s dying injunction had forbidden my uncle to allow me to embark in a seafaring life.

INT. PLAIN ENGLISH ROOM - NIGHT - FLASHBACK

Older youth Walton, papers of verse scattered, crushed by failure.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
I also became a poet and for one year lived in a paradise of my own creation. You are well acquainted with my failure and how heavily I bore the disappointment. But just at that time I inherited the fortune of my cousin, and my thoughts were turned into the channel of their earlier bent.

EXT. NORTH SEA WHALER - DECK - DAY - FLASHBACK

Walton, harder now, works among whale-fishers—cold, rope-burned hands, sleepless eyes. He hauls, climbs, endures.

Night: he studies mathematics and charts by a swinging lantern while men sleep.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
Six years have passed since I resolved on my present undertaking. I accompanied the whale-fishers on several expeditions to the North Sea. I voluntarily endured cold, famine, thirst, and want of sleep. Twice I hired myself as an under-mate in a Greenland whaler, and acquitted myself to admiration.

A CAPTAIN clasps his shoulder, offering advancement. Walton’s pride flickers—then he looks north again.

INT. WALTON'S LODGING - ST. PETERSBURGH - NIGHT

Back to the letter. Walton’s face is open, almost pleading with the page.

ROBERT WALTON
And now, dear Margaret, do I not deserve to accomplish some great purpose? My life might have been passed in ease and luxury, but I preferred glory to every enticement that wealth placed in my path. Oh, that some encouraging voice would answer in the affirmative!

He signs with care.

ROBERT WALTON
Farewell, my dear, excellent Margaret. Heaven shower down blessings on you, and save me, that I may again and again testify my gratitude for all your love and kindness.
Your affectionate brother, R. Walton.

EXT. SLEDGE ROAD - RUSSIA - DAY

Sledges fly over snow. Walton rides, wrapped in furs, jolted and exhilarated. The white world streams past.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
This is the most favourable period for travelling in Russia. They fly quickly over the snow in their sledges. I have no ambition to lose my life on the post-road between St. Petersburgh and Archangel.

EXT. ARCHANGEL HARBOUR - DAY

Ice, masts, breath-smoke. Walton inspects a stout vessel. Hard-faced sailors load casks.

INT. ARCHANGEL LODGING - NIGHT

March cold. Walton at another desk, letter before him. Lonelier now.

ROBERT WALTON
How slowly the time passes here, encompassed as I am by frost and snow! Yet a second step is taken towards my enterprise. I have hired a vessel and am occupied in collecting my sailors.

He stops. The room is empty. The silence presses.

ROBERT WALTON
But I have one want which I have never yet been able to satisfy. I have no friend, Margaret. When I am glowing with the enthusiasm of success, there will be none to participate my joy; if I am assailed by disappointment, no one will endeavour to sustain me in dejection.

He presses his knuckles to his brow.

ROBERT WALTON
I desire the company of a man who could sympathise with me, whose eyes would reply to mine. I am too ardent in execution and too impatient of difficulties. I greatly need a friend who would have sense enough not to despise me as romantic, and affection enough for me to endeavour to regulate my mind.

EXT. ARCHANGEL DOCKS - DAY

Walton walks with LIEUTENANT WILLOUGHBY—English, upright, hungry for advancement—and MASTER FLETCHER—mild-eyed, quiet, strong hands, an uneducated gentleness in his bearing.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
My lieutenant is a man of wonderful courage and enterprise; madly desirous of glory—or rather of advancement in his profession. He retains some of the noblest endowments of humanity.

Willoughby snaps orders; men move smartly.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
The master is remarkable for his gentleness and the mildness of his discipline—integrity and dauntless courage. I cannot overcome an intense distaste to the usual brutality exercised on board ship. I felt myself peculiarly fortunate in being able to secure his services.

Fletcher steadies a nervous young sailor’s load without shame. The boy nods, grateful.

INT. ARCHANGEL LODGING - NIGHT

Walton finishes the thought to Margaret, softer.

ROBERT WALTON
I shall do nothing rashly; you know me sufficiently to confide in my prudence and considerateness whenever the safety of others is committed to my care.

He seals the letter.

EXT. ARCTIC SEA - DAY

Walton’s ship drives among floes. White desolation. Men on deck watch the ice close and open.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
I write a few lines in haste to say that I am safe, and well advanced on my voyage. There is something at work in my soul which I do not understand.

EXT. ARCTIC SEA - PACK ICE - DAY

The ship locked fast. Endless ice. Fog. The crew murmurs. Walton stands at the rail, glass to his eye.

Through the mist: a low sledge, dogs, a figure of gigantic stature driving north at impossible speed—then gone into the white.

LIEUTENANT WILLOUGHBY
A savage? On this ice?

ROBERT WALTON
No savage I ever heard of. Mark the course.

EXT. ARCTIC SEA - PACK ICE - DAY

Next morning. The ice loosens in broken floes. Sailors shout—another sledge, wrecked, one dog living, a man half-dead upon the drift.

They haul him aboard: VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN—emaciated, frostbitten, wild melancholy eyes, ruined gentleman’s clothes. He will not speak until he asks—

VICTOR
Before I come on board your vessel, will you have the kindness to inform me whither you are bound?

ROBERT WALTON
To the northern pole, upon a voyage of discovery.

Only then does Victor consent to be carried to the cabin.

INT. WALTON'S CABIN - NIGHT

Victor wrapped in blankets, fevered, slowly mending under Walton’s care. Walton sits by him with broth and quiet talk.

ROBERT WALTON (V.O.)
I never saw a more interesting creature. His eyes have generally an expression of wildness, and even madness, but there are moments when, if any one performs an act of kindness towards him, his whole countenance is lighted up with a beam of benevolence and sweetness that I never saw equalled.

Victor grasps Walton’s hand with sudden strength.

VICTOR
You seek for knowledge and wisdom, as I once did; and I ardently hope that the gratification of your wishes may not be a serpent to sting you, as mine has been.

INT. WALTON'S CABIN - DAY

Pale Arctic light through the frosted pane. Victor sits propped in the berth, a cup untouched beside him. Walton at the small table, pen ready, ink open.

Victor’s face is gaunt, eyes still luminous. He gathers himself.

VICTOR
I am by birth a Genevese, and my family is one of the most distinguished of that republic. My ancestors had been for many years counsellors and syndics, and my father had filled several public situations with honour and reputation.

Walton writes. Outside, ice groans against the hull.

VICTOR (CONT'D)
He passed his younger days perpetually occupied by the affairs of his country. A variety of circumstances had prevented his marrying early, nor was it until the decline of life that he became a husband and the father of a family.

DISSOLVE TO:

EXT. GENEVA - STREET - DAY

Period live-action; late eighteenth-century dress. ALPHONSE FRANKENSTEIN, fifty, upright, dark coat, grave kind face, walks with purpose among merchants and clerks. Respect follows him—nods, tipped hats.

VICTOR (V.O.)
One of his most intimate friends was a merchant who, from a flourishing state, fell, through numerous mischances, into poverty.

INT. BEAUFORT'S FORMER COUNTING HOUSE - DAY

Empty ledgers. Dust. BEAUFORT, proud, once-prosperous, seals a final payment with stiff dignity. His daughter CAROLINE BEAUFORT—young, fair, resolute—watches, already packing a plain trunk.

VICTOR (V.O.)
This man, whose name was Beaufort, was of a proud and unbending disposition and could not bear to live in poverty and oblivion in the same country where he had formerly been distinguished.

EXT. ROAD TO LUCERNE - DAY

A modest carriage pulls away from Geneva’s walls. Beaufort does not look back. Caroline steadies him.

INT. MEAN LODGING NEAR THE REUSS - LUCERNE - DAY

A bare room. Beaufort sits idle, grief eating him. Coins on the table dwindle. Caroline plaits straw, sews plain work by the window light—earning a pittance.

Months compress: Beaufort sinks onto a sickbed. Caroline attends him day and night, exhaustion in her posture, courage in her eyes.

VICTOR (V.O.)
His daughter attended him with the greatest tenderness, but she saw with despair that their little fund was rapidly decreasing. Caroline Beaufort possessed a mind of an uncommon mould, and her courage rose to support her in her adversity.

INT. MEAN LODGING NEAR THE REUSS - LUCERNE - NIGHT

Beaufort dies in Caroline’s arms. She kneels by the plain coffin, weeping bitterly.

The door opens. Alphonse enters like a protecting spirit—travel-worn, stricken with love and regret. Caroline looks up, broken, and commits herself to his care.

VICTOR (V.O.)
He came like a protecting spirit to the poor girl, who committed herself to his care; and after the interment of his friend he conducted her to Geneva. Two years after this event Caroline became his wife.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - DAY

A quiet wedding blessing. Considerable difference in their ages. Alphonse’s attachment is reverence—he watches Caroline as something precious restored.

VICTOR (V.O.)
There was a sense of justice in my father’s upright mind which rendered it necessary that he should approve highly to love strongly. He strove to shelter her, as a fair exotic is sheltered by the gardener, from every rougher wind.

EXT. ITALIAN COAST - DAY

Sun, sea, a restorative tour. Alphonse and Caroline walk slowly; her health still fragile, his arm ready.

INT. VILLA ROOM - NAPLES - DAY

A newborn in Caroline’s arms. Alphonse’s face breaks into benevolent pleasure. YOUNG VICTOR as infant—dark-eyed, cherished.

VICTOR (V.O.)
I, their eldest child, was born at Naples. My mother’s tender caresses and my father’s smile of benevolent pleasure while regarding me are my first recollections. I was their plaything and their idol, and something better—their child.

EXT. SHORES OF THE LAKE OF COMO - DAY

Years later. Young Victor, about five—slim, dark hair, intent curious face—walks with Caroline past poor cottages. Alphonse has gone ahead toward Milan.

A disconsolate cot in a vale. Half-clothed children. Caroline’s face softens with necessity and memory.

INT. PEASANT COT - LAKE OF COMO - DAY

A PEASANT and PEASANT WOMAN distribute a scanty meal to five hungry babes. Four are dark-eyed, hardy. One girl is thin and very fair—hair the brightest living gold, blue eyes cloudless: young ELIZABETH LAVENZA.

Caroline cannot look away.

PEASANT WOMAN
She is not my child. Daughter of a Milanese nobleman. Her mother was a German and died on giving her birth. The father—whether he died or lingers in the dungeons of Austria, we do not know. His property confiscated. She bloomed here—fairer than a garden rose among dark-leaved brambles.

Caroline kneels to Elizabeth’s level. Elizabeth regards her without fear.

EXT. VILLA - LAKE OF COMO - DAY

Alphonse returns from Milan. In the hall, Elizabeth—lighter than the chamois of the hills—plays with Young Victor. Radiance seems to shed from her looks.

Caroline seeks Alphonse’s permission with her eyes. He understands, and yields.

VICTOR (V.O.)
With his permission my mother prevailed on her rustic guardians to yield their charge. Elizabeth Lavenza became the inmate of my parents’ house—my more than sister—the beautiful and adored companion of all my occupations and my pleasures.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - EVENING

Firelight. Caroline, playful, draws Young Victor close. Elizabeth waits in the doorway, newly dressed, golden hair brushed.

CAROLINE FRANKENSTEIN
I have a pretty present for my Victor—tomorrow he shall have it.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - DAY

Morning. Caroline presents Elizabeth.

Young Victor receives her with childish seriousness—as a possession of his own to protect, love, and cherish.

YOUNG VICTOR
Cousin.

ELIZABETH
Cousin.

They smile. The word is not enough, and both already know it.

VICTOR (V.O.)
I looked upon Elizabeth as mine—mine to protect, love, and cherish. No word, no expression could body forth the kind of relation in which she stood to me—my more than sister, since till death she was to be mine only.

INT. WALTON'S CABIN - DAY

Victor pauses, drained by tenderness remembered. Walton’s pen hovers.

VICTOR
We were brought up together. Harmony was the soul of our companionship.

EXT. CAMPAGNE ON BELRIVE - DAY

The eastern shore of the lake. Mountains. A pleasant house. Young Victor, now a boy of spirited ardour, and Elizabeth, calmer, concentrated, move through gardens and rooms.

Elizabeth reads poets on a terrace, eyes on sublime peaks. Victor crouches over stones, insects, a watch mechanism—investigating causes.

VICTOR (V.O.)
Elizabeth busied herself with the aerial creations of the poets. While my companion contemplated the magnificent appearances of things, I delighted in investigating their causes. The world was to me a secret which I desired to divine.

EXT. GENEVA SCHOOLYARD - DAY

Boys at rough play. Victor holds apart, indifferent to the crowd. HENRY CLERVAL—open face, bright fancy, merchant’s son—pulls him into a mock knightly duel with sticks. Laughter. A bond seals.

HENRY CLERVAL
Again! From the Round Table—have at thee!

VICTOR (V.O.)
Henry Clerval was the son of a merchant of Geneva, an only child. He was deeply read in books of chivalry and romance. No youth could have been more capable of intense application, more ardent in pursuit of knowledge.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - NIGHT

Young Victor, thirteen, finds a volume of Cornelius Agrippa among old books. His eyes light. Alphonse glances at the page and dismisses it lightly.

ALPHONSE FRANKENSTEIN
Ah! Cornelius Agrippa! My dear Victor, do not waste your time upon this; it is sad trash.

Victor’s disappointment hardens into secret resolve.

VICTOR (V.O.)
If, instead of this remark, my father had taken the pains to explain that the principles of Agrippa had been entirely exploded, I should certainly have thrown Agrippa aside. It is even possible that the train of my ideas would never have received the fatal impulse that led to my ruin.

EXT. BELRIVE - THUNDERSTORM - NIGHT

A violent storm over the lake. Lightning shatters an old oak. Young Victor stares at the blasted stump—awed, converted.

VICTOR (V.O.)
I never beheld anything so utterly destroyed. The catastrophe of this tree excited my extreme astonishment; and I eagerly inquired of my father the nature of that power.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - DAY

Caroline tends a scarlet-fever patient—Elizabeth—without rest. Elizabeth recovers. Caroline sinks.

INT. CAROLINE'S BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

Caroline on her deathbed. She joins Victor’s and Elizabeth’s hands.

CAROLINE FRANKENSTEIN
My children, my firmest hopes of future happiness were placed on the prospect of your union. Elizabeth, my love, you must supply my place to my younger children.

She dies. The house is hushed in grief.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - DAY

Alphonse, broken but upright. Victor prepares for university. Elizabeth and Clerval bid him farewell with tears and forced cheer.

ELIZABETH
Write, Victor. Come home to us soon.

HENRY CLERVAL
I would go with you if my father would permit it. Learn all their science—and bring it home.

EXT. ROAD TO INGOLSTADT - DAY

Victor travels alone toward the German university town. Mountains fall behind. His face is set toward knowledge.

INT. UNIVERSITY LECTURE HALL - INGOLSTADT - DAY

Victor sits among students. Notebooks dense with formulae. M. KREMPE lectures at the front—repulsive physiognomy, sharp manners, sound sense underneath.

M. KREMPE
(with a sly smile, aside to Victor)
And how goes Cornelius Agrippa, Herr Frankenstein?

Victor answers only with a thin, absorbed nod. Around him, other students glance—his ardour is already their astonishment.

INT. M. WALDMAN'S LABORATORY - INGOLSTADT - DAY

M. WALDMAN beside Victor at a bench of glass and instruments. Waldman’s gentleness; no pedantry. He guides Victor’s hand to a delicate adjustment.

M. WALDMAN
There. You see how the path clears when one is not afraid of the whole of nature.

Victor’s face: hunger refined into method. Waldman watches him with heartfelt exultation.

M. WALDMAN (CONT'D)
The ancient teachers of this science promised impossibilities, and performed nothing. The modern masters promise very little; they know that metals cannot be transmuted, and that the elixir of life is a chimera. But these philosophers have indeed performed miracles. They penetrate into the recesses of nature, and show how she works in her hiding places.

INT. VICTOR'S APARTMENT - INGOLSTADT - NIGHT

Candles burnt low. Victor still at work as the high steeple outside pales toward morning. Stars disappear in the light. His application no longer fluctuating—ardent, eager, alone.

VICTOR (V.O.)
From this day natural philosophy, and particularly chemistry, became nearly my sole occupation. None but those who have experienced them can conceive of the enticements of science.

INT. WALTON'S CABIN - NIGHT

Victor on the berth, eyes open to the beams. Walton listens, pen ready.

VICTOR
In other studies you go as far as others have gone before you, and there is nothing more to know. But in a scientific pursuit there is continual food for discovery and wonder.

Ice groans along the hull. Walton’s wonder is plain—and his dread.

INT. UNIVERSITY WORKROOMS - INGOLSTADT - DAY

Montage, tight and concrete:

Victor improves a chemical instrument; masters lean in with admiration.

Victor and Krempe over a paper; Krempe grudgingly impressed.

Waldman clasps Victor’s shoulder.

Seasons shift in the tall window light—two years compressed into labour, not travel.

VICTOR (V.O.)
Two years passed in this manner, during which I paid no visit to Geneva. I made some discoveries in the improvement of some chemical instruments, which procured me great esteem at the university.

INT. VICTOR'S APARTMENT - INGOLSTADT - NIGHT

Victor stands over anatomical plates, skull, diagrams of the human frame. A lamp. His finger traces muscle, vein, the question he cannot leave.

VICTOR (V.O.)
One of the phenomena which had peculiarly attracted my attention was the structure of the human frame. Whence, I often asked myself, did the principle of life proceed?

He closes the book. Resolve hardens.

VICTOR (V.O.)
It was a bold question. Yet with how many things are we upon the brink of becoming acquainted, if cowardice or carelessness did not restrain our inquiries.

EXT. CHURCHYARD - INGOLSTADT - NIGHT

Victor with a dark lantern among stones and open earth. No trembling at superstition—only study. He kneels where the soil is turned. Watches decay without flinching.

VICTOR (V.O.)
To examine the causes of life, we must first have recourse to death. Darkness had no effect upon my fancy, and a churchyard was to me merely the receptacle of bodies deprived of life.

INT. CHARNEL-HOUSE VAULT - NIGHT

Damp stone. Victor moves among the unsupportable: wasted forms, the worm’s inheritance of eye and brain. He examines, analyses, pauses over minutiae of causation.

His face in lantern-glow: not madness—method pushed past delicacy.

VICTOR (V.O.)
I saw how the fine form of man was degraded and wasted. I beheld the corruption of death succeed to the blooming cheek of life.

A beat of silence. Then—on his face—sudden illumination. He steadies himself against stone, dizzy.

VICTOR (V.O.)
Until from the midst of this darkness a sudden light broke in upon me—a light so brilliant and wondrous, yet so simple, that I became dizzy with the immensity of the prospect.

INT. VICTOR'S APARTMENT - INGOLSTADT - DAWN

Victor bursts in, exhausted, exalted. Instruments. Notes. He works through the grey light without removing his coat.

Days and nights suggested in the wreck of candles, the stagger of his posture, then stillness—certainty.

VICTOR (V.O.)
After days and nights of incredible labour and fatigue, I succeeded in discovering the cause of generation and life. Nay, more—I became myself capable of bestowing animation upon lifeless matter.

He stares at his own hands as if they belonged to another age.

INT. WALTON'S CABIN - NIGHT

Walton leans forward, eagerness naked in his eyes. Victor meets that look and stops him with a raised hand.

VICTOR
I see by your eagerness and the wonder and hope which your eyes express, my friend, that you expect to be informed of the secret. That cannot be.

Walton sinks back, stricken but obedient.

VICTOR
Listen patiently until the end of my story, and you will easily perceive why I am reserved upon that subject. I will not lead you on, unguarded and ardent as I then was, to your destruction and infallible misery.

VICTOR (CONT'D)
Learn from me, if not by my precepts, at least by my example, how dangerous is the acquirement of knowledge—and how much happier that man is who believes his native town to be the world, than he who aspires to become greater than his nature will allow.

INT. VICTOR'S APARTMENT - INGOLSTADT - NIGHT

Victor alone among sketches—human proportions, then larger. He hesitates, paces, returns. Imagination exalted past simpler animals.

VICTOR (V.O.)
When I found so astonishing a power placed within my hands, I hesitated a long time concerning the manner in which I should employ it. I doubted at first whether I should attempt the creation of a being like myself, or one of simpler organization.

He draws a figure—eight feet, proportionably large—and sets his jaw.

VICTOR (V.O.)
As the minuteness of the parts formed a great hindrance to my speed, I resolved to make the being of a gigantic stature—about eight feet in height, and proportionably large.

EXT. CHURCHYARD AND CHARNEL GROUND - NIGHT

Victor collects with profane care: bones, materials wrapped and borne away. The moon on his labour. His cheek already paling.

VICTOR (V.O.)
Who shall conceive the horrors of my secret toil as I dabbled among the unhallowed damps of the grave, or tortured the living animal to animate the lifeless clay?

INT. SLAUGHTER-HOUSE - NIGHT

Blood, hooks, raw matter. Victor’s human nature turns with loathing—then the eagerness drives him on. He takes what he came for.

INT. VICTOR'S WORKSHOP - TOP OF THE HOUSE - NIGHT

A solitary chamber, almost a cell, separated by gallery and stair. Filthy creation: instruments, vats, the vast unfinished form under cloth. Victor’s eyeballs starting from their sockets as he works the details of fibre, muscle, vein.

Rain at the high small window. His person emaciated; confinement written in every line of him.

VICTOR (V.O.)
In a solitary chamber, or rather cell, at the top of the house, I kept my workshop of filthy creation. The dissecting room and the slaughter-house furnished many of my materials.

He stitches, measures, adjusts by dying candle. Sometimes on the brink of certainty—fails—clings to the next hour.

VICTOR (V.O.)
Life and death appeared to me ideal bounds, which I should first break through, and pour a torrent of light into our dark world. A new species would bless me as its creator and source. No father could claim the gratitude of his child so completely as I should deserve theirs.

INT. VICTOR'S WORKSHOP - TOP OF THE HOUSE - NIGHT

November. Dreary night of the season. Rain patters against the panes. The candle is nearly burnt out.

The finished form lies on the table—yellow skin, lustrous black hair, pearly teeth, watery eyes closed.

Victor’s hand trembles as he applies the instruments of life.

A convulsive motion agitates the limbs.

The dull yellow eye of THE CREATURE opens. It breathes hard. Its limbs jerk. It rises—gigantic, hideous in the living flesh that seemed beautiful in the chosen parts.

Victor staggers back, horror flooding every feature.

VICTOR (V.O.)
How can I describe my emotions at this catastrophe, or how delineate the wretch whom with such infinite pains and care I had endeavoured to form? His yellow skin scarcely covered the work of muscles and arteries beneath; his hair was of a lustrous black, and flowing; his teeth of a pearly whiteness; but these luxuriances only formed a more horrid contrast with his watery eyes, that seemed almost of the same colour as the dun white sockets in which they were set, his shrivelled complexion and straight black lips.

The Creature reaches toward him—a grin wrinkled into the cheeks.

Victor flees the workshop.

INT. VICTOR'S APARTMENT - INGOLSTADT - NIGHT

Victor paces below in agony. He throws himself on the bed fully clothed, seeking a moment’s forgetfulness.

Sleep brings a nightmare: Elizabeth, in the bloom of health, whom he embraces—then her features change to the corpse of his dead mother, grave-worms crawling in the folds of the flannel.

He wakes with a start. The dim yellow light of the moon discloses the Creature at his bedside—the curtains drawn, the eyes fixed on him, jaws opened, a sound muttered between them while a hand stretched out as if to detain him.

Victor rushes into the courtyard and takes refuge in the furthest corner, trembling, listening for every sound.

EXT. STREETS OF INGOLSTADT - DAWN

Victor wanders, unable to return. Morning light finds him exhausted near an inn.

A coach rattles in. HENRY CLERVAL springs down, radiant.

HENRY CLERVAL
My dear Frankenstein—how glad I am to see you! How fortunate that you should be here at the very moment of my alighting!

Victor tries to smile. His face is a wreck. Clerval’s joy falters into concern.

INT. VICTOR'S APARTMENT - INGOLSTADT - DAY

Victor leads Clerval upstairs, heart hammering. The apartment is empty. No Creature. Relief and dread mingle.

Then Victor collapses into a fever that lasts months—raving of the workshop, of the demoniacal corpse to which he had given life. Clerval nurses him without rest.

INT. VICTOR'S APARTMENT - INGOLSTADT - DAY

Spring light. Victor breaks the seal of a letter. Henry watches from the window.

ELIZABETH (V.O.)
My dearest Cousin, you have been ill, very ill, and even the constant letters of dear kind Henry are not sufficient to reassure me. You are forbidden to write—to hold a pen; yet one word from you, dear Victor, is necessary to calm our apprehensions. Get well—and return to us. You will find a happy, cheerful home and friends who love you dearly.

Victor's face softens. He reads on, hungry for home.

ELIZABETH (V.O.)
How pleased you would be to remark the improvement of our Ernest! He is now sixteen and full of activity and spirit. Little alteration, except the growth of our dear children, has taken place since you left us. The blue lake and snow-clad mountains—they never change.

A faint smile. Then a new name on the page holds him.

ELIZABETH (V.O.)
Since you left us, but one change has taken place in our little household. Do you remember on what occasion Justine Moritz entered our family? Madame Moritz, her mother, was a widow with four children, of whom Justine was the third. Through a strange perversity her mother could not endure her, and my aunt prevailed to allow her to live at our house. Justine, you may remember, was a great favourite of yours.

Victor nods almost imperceptibly—memory of a frank, happy face.

ELIZABETH (V.O.)
When my dearest aunt died, poor Justine attended her with the most anxious affection. One by one her brothers and sister died; her mother called her home, then accused her of having caused their deaths. Madame Moritz died on the first approach of cold weather. Justine has just returned to us; and I assure you I love her tenderly. She is very clever and gentle, and extremely pretty.

ELIZABETH (V.O.)
I must say also a few words of little darling William. He is very tall of his age, with sweet laughing blue eyes, dark eyelashes, and curling hair. When he smiles, two little dimples appear on each cheek. Write, dearest Victor,—one line—one word will be a blessing to us. Adieu! my cousin; take care of yourself; and, I entreat you, write!
Elizabeth Lavenza. Geneva, March 18th, 17—.

Victor lowers the letter, eyes wet.

VICTOR
Dear, dear Elizabeth! I will write instantly and relieve them from the anxiety they must feel.

He drags paper toward him. Henry steadies his shoulder.

INT. VICTOR'S APARTMENT - INGOLSTADT - DAY

SUPER: A fortnight later.

Victor stands dressed, steady. Sun fills the room. The chemical apparatus is gone. The chamber that was his laboratory has been changed—new walls, plain furniture, no instruments.

Henry opens the door, bright with purpose.

HENRY CLERVAL
One of your first duties, my friend. The professors. They ask after you.

Victor's jaw tightens. He nods once and follows.

INT. M. WALDMAN'S STUDY - UNIVERSITY - DAY

Books, specimens, soft light. M. WALDMAN—kind, silvered, warm—clasps Victor's hand, then Henry's.

M. WALDMAN
M. Frankenstein. Returned to us. And this is M. Clerval—welcome.

He turns back to Victor with genuine pride.

M. WALDMAN (CONT'D)
The astonishing progress you made in the sciences—I have not ceased to speak of it. You left us at a height few students ever reach.

Victor goes rigid. The praise is a blade. Glassware on a side table catches the light like instruments of torture.

Henry sees Victor's face and steps in at once.

HENRY CLERVAL
You must forgive me, Monsieur—I am wholly ignorant of these matters. Perhaps another subject—

Waldman yields, genial. Victor thanks Henry only with his eyes.

INT. UNIVERSITY CORRIDOR AND KREMPE'S ROOMS - DAY

M. KREMPE—blunt, loud, impatient—blocks their path, then ushers them in with no ceremony.

M. KREMPE
D—n the fellow! Why, M. Clerval, I assure you he has outstript us all. Ay, stare if you please; but it is nevertheless true. A youngster who, but a few years ago, believed in Cornelius Agrippa as firmly as in the gospel, has now set himself at the head of the university.

He clocks Victor's suffering face and barks a laugh.

M. KREMPE (CONT'D)
Ay, ay—M. Frankenstein is modest; an excellent quality in a young man. Young men should be diffident of themselves, you know, M. Clerval.

Krempe launches into a eulogy on himself. Victor breathes again.

INT. SHARED STUDY - INGOLSTADT - DAY

Scrolls, grammars, Eastern texts spread between them. Henry reads aloud in Persian; Victor follows—for escape.

Through the window: summer light thickens, then thins toward autumn. Leaves turn. Snow dusts the sill.

HENRY CLERVAL
Life in these writers—a warm sun and a garden of roses. Not the manly thunder of Greece and Rome.

VICTOR
Their melancholy is soothing. Their joy elevating. I read only to understand—and they repay me.

HENRY CLERVAL
Geneva must wait until the snows break. I will not have you leave me in a strange place with no acquaintance made.

VICTOR
I feel the delay bitterly. But I will not leave you so.

EXT. COUNTRYSIDE NEAR INGOLSTADT - DAY

May. Hedges in flower. Victor and Henry walk a pedestrian tour—packs light, pace easy. Victor's color is high; his step has length.

Birdsong. A stream. Peasant children laugh in a lane; Victor answers their waves without flinching.

VICTOR (V.O.)
Clerval called forth the better feelings of my heart. He again taught me to love the aspect of nature, and the cheerful faces of children. A selfish pursuit had cramped and narrowed me, until his gentleness warmed and opened my senses.

Henry invents a wild Eastern tale as they climb a rise; Victor laughs—true laughter.

EXT. COUNTRY ROAD NEAR INGOLSTADT - DAY

Sunday afternoon. They return toward the college. Peasants dance in a field. Victor bounds ahead, unbridled, almost boyish.

HENRY CLERVAL
There—there is my friend again.

Victor turns, radiant, and throws an arm toward the open sky.

INT. VICTOR'S APARTMENT - INGOLSTADT - DAY

Travel dust still on their boots. A letter waits on the table—his father's hand. Victor breaks it with eager fingers. Joy first. Then the blood leaves his face.

ALPHONSE (V.O.)
My dear Victor, you have probably waited impatiently for a letter to fix the date of your return. But that would be a cruel kindness, and I dare not do it. William is dead!—that sweet child, whose smiles delighted and warmed my heart, who was so gentle, yet so gay! Victor, he is murdered!

The letter shakes in Victor's grip. Henry starts forward.

ALPHONSE (V.O.)
Last Thursday (May 7th), I, my niece, and your two brothers, went to walk in Plainpalais. The evening was warm and serene. Entering the grounds, we sat on a bank overlooking the lake. William and Ernest ran on ahead. Ernest came running back, saying that William was lost. We searched until night. About five in the morning I discovered my lovely boy, whom the night before I had seen blooming and active in health, stretched on the grass livid and motionless; the print of the murderer’s finger was on his neck.

Victor sinks into a chair. Henry steadies him.

ALPHONSE (V.O.)
Come, dearest Victor; you alone can console Elizabeth. She accuses herself of having caused the death of my brother, for it appears that he had strayed from her to seek a hiding-place for a valuable miniature that she wore. She thinks that, having possessed himself of the picture, the murderer must have been disturbed in his design, and have murdered my child to conceal his theft. She is much interested concerning the fate of poor Justine Moritz, who is accused of the murder.

VICTOR
William—my brother—

He rises, already packing in a frenzy. Henry helps without question.

EXT. GATES OF GENEVA - NIGHT

Victor arrives in a storm. Lightning over the Alps. The lake black. He cannot bring himself to enter at once—walks toward Plainpalais.

EXT. PLAINPALAIS - NIGHT

Thunder. In a flash of lightning Victor sees among the trees a gigantic figure—the Creature—climbing the rocks of a nearby precipice with superhuman speed.

VICTOR
(whispered)
It is he. The murderer of my brother.

Horror and certainty root him. Rain lashes his face.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - DAY

Alphonse embraces his son, aged by grief. Elizabeth, pale, rushes to Victor. ERNEST, now a youth, stands aside, eyes red.

ELIZABETH
Your arrival, my dear cousin, fills me with hope. You perhaps will find some means to justify my poor guiltless Justine.

VICTOR
She is innocent. That at least I know.

But he cannot say how.

INT. COURT OF GENEVA - DAY

A crowded chamber. Stone walls, high windows, black-robed judges on the bench. The gallery presses forward, hungry for spectacle.

VICTOR sits with ALPHONSE and ELIZABETH among the witnesses. His face is bloodless. He grips the rail until his knuckles whiten.

JUSTINE is led in—young, dressed in mourning, manacled. Her countenance, always engaging, is rendered by solemnity exquisitely beautiful. She does not tremble, though thousands gaze and execrate.

She throws her eyes round the court and discovers the Frankenstein family. A tear dims her eye. She recovers. A look of sorrowful affection attests her utter guiltlessness.

VICTOR (V.O.)
During the whole of this wretched mockery of justice I suffered living torture. It was to be decided whether the result of my curiosity and lawless devices would cause the death of two of my fellow beings—one a smiling babe, the other far more dreadfully murdered.

The ADVOCATE states the charge. A MARKET-WOMAN testifies: Justine out the whole night; perceived near the spot toward morning; looked strangely; returned a confused answer. Servants recount her return at eight, her earnest demand for news of the child, her violent hysterics when shown the body.

The miniature is produced—the portrait of Caroline Frankenstein found in Justine’s pocket.

ELIZABETH
(faltering, rising)
It is the same which, an hour before the child had been missed, I placed round his neck.

A murmur of horror fills the court. Justine’s countenance alters—surprise, horror, misery.

JUSTINE
God knows how entirely I am innocent. But I do not pretend that my protestations should acquit me; I rest my innocence on a plain and simple explanation of the facts which have been adduced against me.

She draws a steadying breath.

JUSTINE (CONT'D)
By the permission of Elizabeth, I passed the evening of that night at the house of an aunt at Chêne, a village about a league from Geneva. On my return, at about nine o’clock, I met a man who asked me if I had seen anything of the child who was lost. I was alarmed, and passed several hours in looking for him. The gates of Geneva were shut. I was forced to remain several hours of the night in a barn belonging to a cottage. Towards morning I believed that I slept for a few minutes. It was dawn. I quitted my asylum that I might again endeavour to find the child. If I had gone near the spot where his body lay, it was without my knowledge.

Her voice falters, then steadies.

JUSTINE (CONT'D)
Concerning the picture I can give no account. I know how heavily and fatally this one circumstance weighs against me, but I have no power of explaining it. I believe that I have no enemy on earth, and none surely would have been so wicked as to destroy me wantonly. Did the murderer place it there? I know of no opportunity afforded him for so doing.

She looks to the judges.

JUSTINE (CONT'D)
I commit my cause to the justice of my judges, yet I see no room for hope. I beg permission to have a few witnesses examined concerning my character, and if their testimony shall not overweigh my supposed guilt, I must be condemned, although I would pledge my salvation on my innocence.

Several neighbors and servants speak well of her—but fear renders them timorous. Their praise dies in half-voices.

Elizabeth, violently agitated, rises.

ELIZABETH
I am the cousin of the unhappy child who was murdered, or rather his sister, for I was educated by and have lived with his parents ever since and even long before his birth. I am well acquainted with the accused. During all that period she appeared to me the most amiable and benevolent of human creatures. She nursed Madame Frankenstein, my aunt, in her last illness, with the greatest affection and care. She was warmly attached to the child who is now dead and acted towards him like a most affectionate mother. For my own part, I do not hesitate to say that, notwithstanding all the evidence produced against her, I believe and rely on her perfect innocence. She had no temptation for such an action. As to the bauble on which the chief proof rests, if she had earnestly desired it, I should have willingly given it to her.

A murmur of approbation—excited by Elizabeth’s generous interference, not in favour of Justine. Public indignation turns on the accused with renewed violence.

Victor’s face is a mask of agony. He can sustain it no longer. He rushes out of the court.

INT. COURT OF GENEVA - CORRIDOR - DAY

Victor staggers into the stone passage, gasping.

VICTOR (V.O.)
The tortures of the accused did not equal mine. She was sustained by innocence, but the fangs of remorse tore my bosom and would not forgo their hold.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - VICTOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

Victor alone. No sleep. Candle burned to a stub. He paces, sits, presses his fists to his temples.

EXT. COURT OF GENEVA - MORNING

Victor approaches the entrance, lips and throat parched. OFFICER MERLE, recognizing him, meets him on the steps.

OFFICER MERLE
The ballots have been thrown. They were all black. Justine Moritz is condemned.

Victor sways.

OFFICER MERLE (CONT'D)
She has already confessed her guilt. That evidence was hardly required in so glaring a case, but I am glad of it. None of our judges like to condemn a criminal upon circumstantial evidence, be it ever so decisive.

Victor stares, uncomprehending, and hastens away.

INT. PRISON CELL - GENEVA - DAY

Justine on a straw pallet, eyes swollen. Elizabeth and Victor enter. Justine rises and falls into Elizabeth’s arms.

JUSTINE
I do not fear to die. That pang is past. God raises my weakness and gives me courage to endure the worst. I leave a sad and bitter world; and if you remember me and think of me as of one unjustly condemned, I am resigned to the fate awaiting me.

ELIZABETH
I believed you guiltless—I still believe so.

JUSTINE
I did confess; but I confessed a lie. I confessed, that I might obtain absolution; but now that falsehood lies heavier at my heart than all my other sins. The priest threatened and menaced, until I almost began to think that I was the monster he said I was.

She turns to Victor, gentle even now.

JUSTINE (CONT'D)
I leave you with a heavy heart. Farewell, sweet lady—dearest Elizabeth, my beloved and only friend. Live, and be happy, and make others so.

EXT. PLACE OF EXECUTION - GENEVA - DAY

A distant crowd. Bells. Victor stands apart, shattered. Justine is led out. The sentence is carried through.

VICTOR (V.O.)
The poor victim, who on the morrow was to pass the awful boundary between life and death, felt not, as I did, such deep and bitter agony. I was seized by remorse and the sense of guilt, which hurried me away to a hell of intense tortures such as no language can describe.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - LIBRARY - GENEVA - DAY

Elizabeth meets him, desperate, changed.

ELIZABETH
When I reflect that they are all murdered by her I once so much esteemed, I no longer see the world and its works as they before appeared to me. Justine died; she rested; and I now sleep in the faith that she is happy. But William—William, that sweet child—

VICTOR
She was innocent.

ELIZABETH
I wish that I were to die with her. I cannot live with these unalterable horrors.

Alphonse tries to comfort them both; his own grief is a quiet ruin.

EXT. SHORES OF LAKE GENEVA - DAY

Weeks of gloom. Victor wanders alone, unable to rest. The family removes to Belrive. He takes the boat at night and drifts under the stars, sometimes tempted by the water’s peace.

EXT. VALLEY OF CHAMOUNIX - DAY

Alphonse urges a journey to distract them. Victor, Elizabeth, Ernest ride toward the mountains. Sublime peaks rise. Victor’s spirits lift a fraction in the cold air—then sink again.

EXT. SOURCES OF THE ARVEIRON - DAY

Victor stands alone beside the glacier's birth. An icy wall overhangs him. Abrupt mountain sides rise sheer. A few shattered pines scatter the ground.

The solemn silence breaks only by brawling waves, the thunder of an avalanche, the cracking of accumulated ice.

These sublime scenes elevate him from littleness of feeling. They do not remove his grief—they subdue and tranquillise it.

INT. INN AT CHAMOUNIX - NIGHT

Victor sleeps. About his rest congregate the shapes of the day: unstained snowy mountain-tops, glittering pinnacles, pine woods, ragged bare ravines, an eagle soaring amidst clouds.

INT. INN AT CHAMOUNIX - MORNING

He wakes. Dark melancholy clouds every thought.

Rain pours in torrents. Thick mists hide the summits.

He rises with resolve. His mule is brought to the door.

VICTOR
(to himself)
What are rain and storm to me?

EXT. PATH TO MONTANVERT - DAY

Precipitous ascent. The path cuts into continual short windings.

A scene terrifically desolate. Traces of winter avalanche everywhere: trees broken and strewed.

Higher, the path intersects ravines of snow. Stones continually roll from above. Sombre pines add severity. Rain pours from the dark sky.

Victor climbs on, alone, soaked, driven.

VICTOR (V.O.)
Alas! Why does man boast of sensibilities superior to those apparent in the brute? It only renders them more necessary beings. If our impulses were confined to hunger, thirst, and desire, we might be nearly free.

He pauses on a winding, rain streaking his face.

VICTOR (V.O.)
We rest; a dream has power to poison sleep. We rise; one wandering thought pollutes the day. Nought may endure but mutability.

EXT. MONTANVERT - ROCK OVERLOOK - DAY

Nearly noon. Victor sits upon the rock that overlooks the sea of ice.

A mist covers the glacier. A breeze dissipates the cloud. He rises and descends upon the ice.

EXT. SEA OF ICE - DAY

The surface is very uneven—rising like the waves of a troubled sea, descending low, interspersed by rifts that sink deep.

Victor crosses with caution. Nearly two hours.

He remains in a recess of the rock, gazing. The vast river of ice winds among its dependent mountains. Icy and glittering peaks shine in the sunlight over the clouds.

His heart, before sorrowful, swells with something like joy.

VICTOR
Wandering spirits, if indeed ye wander, and do not rest in your narrow beds, allow me this faint happiness, or take me, as your companion, away from the joys of life.

As he says this he suddenly beholds the figure of a man at some distance, advancing toward him with superhuman speed.

The figure bounds over the crevices in the ice. As he approaches, his stature seems to exceed that of a man.

It is THE CREATURE—gigantic, yellowed skin stretched over taut muscle, lustrous black hair, watery eyes, black lips, countenance of bitter anguish combined with disdain and malignity—advances in rough garments scavenged and ill-fitting.

Victor trembles with rage and horror.

VICTOR
Devil, do you dare approach me? And do not you fear the fierce vengeance of my arm wreaked on your miserable head? Begone, vile insect! Or rather, stay, that I may trample you to dust! And, oh! That I could, with the extinction of your miserable existence, restore those victims whom you have so diabolically murdered!

THE CREATURE
I expected this reception. All men hate the wretched; how, then, must I be hated, who am miserable beyond all living things! Yet you, my creator, detest and spurn me, thy creature, to whom thou art bound by ties only dissoluble by the annihilation of one of us. You purpose to kill me. How dare you sport thus with life? Do your duty towards me, and I will do mine towards you and the rest of mankind. If you will comply with my conditions, I will leave them and you at peace; but if you refuse, I will glut the maw of death, until it be satiated with the blood of your remaining friends.

VICTOR
Abhorred monster! Fiend that thou art! The tortures of hell are too mild a vengeance for thy crimes. Wretched devil! You reproach me with your creation, come on, then, that I may extinguish the spark which I so negligently bestowed.

Victor springs on the Creature. The Creature easily eludes him.

THE CREATURE
Be calm! I entreat you to hear me before you give vent to your hatred on my devoted head. Have I not suffered enough, that you seek to increase my misery? Life, although it may only be an accumulation of anguish, is dear to me, and I will defend it. Remember, thou hast made me more powerful than thyself; my height is superior to thine, my joints more supple. But I will not be tempted to set myself in opposition to thee. I am thy creature, and I will be even mild and docile to my natural lord and king if thou wilt also perform thy part, the which thou owest me. Oh, Frankenstein, be not equitable to every other and trample upon me alone, to whom thy justice, and even thy clemency and affection, is most due. Remember that I am thy creature; I ought to be thy Adam, but I am rather the fallen angel, whom thou drivest from joy for no misdeed. Everywhere I see bliss, from which I alone am irrevocably excluded. I was benevolent and good; misery made me a fiend. Make me happy, and I shall again be virtuous.

VICTOR
Begone! I will not hear you. There can be no community between you and me; we are enemies. Begone, or let us try our strength in a fight, in which one must fall.

THE CREATURE
How can I move thee? Will no entreaties cause thee to turn a favourable eye upon thy creature, who implores thy goodness and compassion? Believe me, Frankenstein, I was benevolent; my soul glowed with love and humanity; but am I not alone, miserably alone? You, my creator, abhor me; what hope can I gather from your fellow creatures, who owe me nothing? They spurn and hate me. The desert mountains and dreary glaciers are my refuge. I have wandered here many days; the caves of ice, which I only do not fear, are a dwelling to me, and the only one which man does not grudge. These bleak skies I hail, for they are kinder to me than your fellow beings. If the multitude of mankind knew of my existence, they would do as you do, and arm themselves for my destruction. Shall I not then hate them who abhor me? Listen to my tale. The guilty are allowed, by human laws, bloody as they are, to speak in their own defence before they are condemned. Listen to me, Frankenstein. You accuse me of murder, and yet you would, with a satisfied conscience, destroy your own creature. Oh, praise the eternal justice of man!

Victor’s rage falters into a bitter necessity of hearing.

THE CREATURE (CONT'D)
Come to the hut upon the mountain. The sun is yet high in the heavens; before it descends to hide itself behind your snowy precipices and illuminate another world, you will have heard my story and can decide.

EXT. MOUNTAIN HUT - DAY

Victor follows at a distance. The Creature leads him to a rude wooden hut, kindles a fire, and sits. Victor remains near the entrance, resolved to hear.

INT. HUT ON THE MOUNTAIN - DAY

Firelight on the Creature’s terrible face. Victor opposite, rigid.

THE CREATURE
It is with considerable difficulty that I remember the original era of my being; all the events of that period appear confused and indistinct. A strange multiplicity of sensations seized me, and I saw, felt, heard, and smelt at the same time.

EXT. FOREST NEAR INGOLSTADT - DAY - FLASHBACK

The Creature stumbles among trees, newborn senses overwhelmed. Light blinds him. He covers his eyes. Hunger and thirst drive him to a brook. Berries. The cold of night makes him weep.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
I was a poor, helpless, miserable wretch; I knew, and could distinguish, nothing; but feeling pain invade me on all sides, I sat down and wept.

EXT. FOREST CAMPFIRE - NIGHT - FLASHBACK

He finds a fire left by beggars, delights in its warmth, burns his hand, learns to feed it with wood.

EXT. VILLAGE NEAR THE FOREST - DAY - FLASHBACK

He enters a village seeking food. Villagers scream. Stones and weapons drive him out, bruised and bleeding.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
The whole village was roused; some fled, some attacked me, until, grievously bruised by stones and many other kinds of missile weapons, I escaped to the open country and fearfully took refuge in a low hovel.

EXT. HOVEL BESIDE THE COTTAGE - NIGHT - FLASHBACK

A mean shed built against a cottage of neat plainness. The Creature crawls in, finds it empty of occupant, and lies on straw, grateful for shelter.

INT. HOVEL BESIDE THE COTTAGE - DAY - FLASHBACK

Through a chink he watches the cottagers: DE LACEY—blind, white-haired, dignified in poverty—AGATHA—young, gentle, worn hands—and FELIX—lean, dark-eyed, sorrow etched in his face.

INT. COTTAGE - DAY - FLASHBACK

Dawn. Agatha arranges the cottage and prepares a sparse meal. De Lacey sits by the cold hearth. Felix eats quickly and departs with an axe.

Through the chink, the Creature watches, motionless.

EXT. COTTAGE GARDEN AND FIELDS - DAY - FLASHBACK

Felix labours out of doors. Agatha works within sight. De Lacey, alone by the doorway, feels his way to a wooden stool and takes up his guitar.

Agatha brings her father water; Felix, returning, steadies the old man's arm. Every little office of affection performed with gentleness.

INT. HOVEL BESIDE THE COTTAGE - NIGHT - FLASHBACK

The Creature steals a portion of the cottagers' store—then freezes as he sees Agatha set food before De Lacey and reserve none for herself. Felix does the same.

The Creature looks down at the stolen food. Slowly he sets it back toward their side and withdraws.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
This trait of kindness moved me sensibly. When I found that in doing this I inflicted pain on the cottagers, I abstained, and satisfied myself with berries, nuts, and roots.

EXT. COTTAGE - NIGHT - FLASHBACK

The Creature takes Felix's tools. He cuts and stacks firing—enough for several days—in a great pile outside the cottage door. Then he melts back into the trees.

EXT. COTTAGE - DAY - FLASHBACK

Morning. Agatha opens the door—astonished at the great pile of wood. Felix joins her; surprise breaks his habitual sadness. He does not go to the forest that day.

INT. HOVEL BESIDE THE COTTAGE - DAY - FLASHBACK

Several revolutions of the moon. The Creature presses to the chink, lips moving silently as the cottagers speak.

THE CREATURE
(whispered, harsh)
Fire... milk... bread... wood.

He listens again.

THE CREATURE
(soft wonder)
Father. Agatha. Felix.

Delight breaks over his ruined face.

INT. COTTAGE - NIGHT - FLASHBACK

Felix reads aloud to De Lacey and Agatha. The Creature at the chink slowly understands: the same sounds as speech, signs upon the paper.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
I ardently longed to comprehend these also. I easily perceived that, although I eagerly longed to discover myself to the cottagers, I ought not to make the attempt until I had first become master of their language.

EXT. POOL IN THE WOODS - DAY - FLASHBACK

Thaw. The Creature comes upon a transparent pool. He leans to drink—and starts back from his own reflection.

Yellow eyes. Scarred yellow skin. Enormous frame. Hideous proportions.

He turns his face away, filled with despondence and mortification.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
Alas! I did not yet entirely know the fatal effects of this miserable deformity.

INT. HUT ON THE MOUNTAIN - DAY

The mountain fire between them. Victor's face is set.

THE CREATURE
I had admired the perfect forms of my cottagers—their grace, beauty, and delicate complexions. When I became fully convinced that I was in reality the monster that I am, I was filled with the bitterest sensations of despondence and mortification.

INT. COTTAGE - DAY - FLASHBACK

Spring. A stranger arrives—SAFIE, dark-eyed, graceful, in foreign dress. Felix’s sorrow breaks into joy. He teaches her French with passionate care. The Creature listens and learns with her—words, history, the order of society.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
Presently I found that the Arabian, whose name was Safie, understood French only imperfectly. Felix became her instructor. My days were spent in close attention that I might more speedily master the language. I improved more rapidly than the Arabian.

INT. HOVEL BESIDE THE COTTAGE - NIGHT - FLASHBACK

By stolen candle the Creature reads books found in a leathern portmanteau: Paradise Lost, Plutarch’s Lives, The Sorrows of Werter—and Victor’s own laboratory journal.

Tears cut tracks on his cheeks as he reads the journal’s minute, horrified description of his formation.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
Like Adam, I was united by no link to any other being—but his state was far different. He had come forth from the hands of God a perfect creature. I was wretched, helpless, and alone. Many times I considered Satan as the fitter emblem of my condition.

He flings the journal down.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
Hateful day when I received life! Accursed creator! Why did you form a monster so hideous that even you turned from me in disgust?

INT. HUT ON THE MOUNTAIN - DAY

Victor flinches. The Creature’s voice softens with remembered hope.

THE CREATURE
I persuaded myself that when the cottagers should become acquainted with my admiration they would compassionate me. I resolved to enter when the blind old man was alone.

INT. COTTAGE - DAY - FLASHBACK

Autumn light. DE LACEY sits alone with his guitar. He plays a mournful air, then lays it aside.

A knock.

DE LACEY
Who is there? Come in.

The Creature enters, ducking the lintel, voice harsh but careful.

THE CREATURE
Pardon this intrusion. I am a traveller in want of a little rest; you would greatly oblige me if you would allow me to remain a few minutes before the fire.

DE LACEY
Enter, and I will try in what manner I can to relieve your wants; but, unfortunately, my children are from home, and as I am blind, I am afraid I shall find it difficult to procure food for you.

THE CREATURE
Do not trouble yourself, my kind host; I have food; it is warmth and rest only that I need.

He sits. Silence. De Lacey turns toward the sound of breathing.

DE LACEY
By your language, stranger, I suppose you are my countryman; are you French?

THE CREATURE
No; but I was educated by a French family and understand that language only. I am now going to claim the protection of some friends, whom I sincerely love, and of whose favour I have some hopes.

DE LACEY
Do not despair. To be friendless is indeed to be unfortunate, but the hearts of men, when unprejudiced by any obvious self-interest, are full of brotherly love and charity. Rely, therefore, on your hopes.

THE CREATURE
They are kind—they are the most excellent creatures in the world; but, unfortunately, they are prejudiced against me. I have good dispositions; my life has been hitherto harmless and in some degree beneficial; but a fatal prejudice clouds their eyes, and where they ought to see a feeling and kind friend, they behold only a detestable monster.

DE LACEY
That is indeed unfortunate; but if you are really blameless, cannot you undeceive them?

THE CREATURE
I am about to undertake that task. I tenderly love these friends; I have, unknown to them, been for many months in the habits of daily kindness towards them.

DE LACEY
I am blind and cannot judge of your countenance, but there is something in your words which persuades me that you are sincere. I am poor and an exile, but it will afford me true pleasure to be in any way serviceable to a human creature.

THE CREATURE
Excellent man! I thank you and accept your generous offer. You raise me from the dust by this kindness. How can I thank you, my best and only benefactor? From your lips first have I heard the voice of kindness directed towards me.

Footsteps outside—Felix, Agatha, Safie returning. The Creature seizes De Lacey's hand, sinks to his knees.

THE CREATURE
Now is the time! Save and protect me! You and your family are the friends whom I seek. Do not you desert me in the hour of trial!

DE LACEY
Great God! Who are you?

The door bursts open. FELIX, AGATHA, and SAFIE freeze in horror. Agatha faints. Safie screams and rushes out. Felix tears the Creature from his father's knees and dashes him to the ground. He strikes with a stick.

The Creature could tear him limb from limb—but his heart sinks. He quits the cottage and flees.

INT. HOVEL BESIDE THE COTTAGE - NIGHT - FLASHBACK

The Creature howls into the dark.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
Cursed, cursed creator! Why did I live? From that moment I declared everlasting war against the species, and more than all, against him who had formed me.

EXT. COTTAGE - NIGHT - FLASHBACK

Wind tears the clouds. The Creature dances with a burning brand around the cottage. He fires the straw and heath. Flames lick the walls with forked tongues. He flees into the woods as the habitation is engulfed.

INT. HUT ON THE MOUNTAIN - DAY

Victor stares, hollow-eyed.

THE CREATURE
I resolved to seek you, my father, my creator. I travelled only at night. Nature decayed around me. The mildness of my nature had fled, and all within me was turned to gall and bitterness.

EXT. DEEP WOOD / RIVER - DAY - FLASHBACK

Early spring. A YOUNG GIRL runs laughing along the precipitous bank—slips—falls into the rapid stream.

The Creature rushes out, battles the current, drags her senseless to shore. A RUSTIC appears, tears the girl from his arms, aims a gun, fires. The Creature sinks, shoulder shattered.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
This was then the reward of my benevolence! I vowed eternal hatred and vengeance to all mankind.

EXT. FIELDS NEAR GENEVA - EVENING - FLASHBACK

The Creature hides among the fields. A beautiful child—WILLIAM FRANKENSTEIN—runs into the recess with the sportiveness of infancy.

The Creature seizes him.

THE CREATURE
Child, what is the meaning of this? I do not intend to hurt you; listen to me.

WILLIAM
Let me go! Monster! Ugly wretch! You wish to eat me and tear me to pieces. You are an ogre. Let me go, or I will tell my papa.

THE CREATURE
Boy, you will never see your father again; you must come with me.

WILLIAM
Hideous monster! Let me go. My papa is a syndic—he is M. Frankenstein—he will punish you. You dare not keep me.

THE CREATURE
Frankenstein! You belong then to my enemy—to him towards whom I have sworn eternal revenge; you shall be my first victim.

The child’s screams are choked as the Creature’s hands close on his throat. William goes still.

The Creature finds the miniature of Caroline about the boy’s neck. Beauty and bitterness war in him. He takes it.

EXT. BARN NEAR GENEVA - NIGHT - FLASHBACK

Justine asleep in the barn, exhausted from searching. The Creature sees her—sees a way to wound his creator further. He plants the miniature in the folds of her dress and flees.

INT. HUT ON THE MOUNTAIN - DAY

The fire sinks lower. The Creature stands opposite Victor.

THE CREATURE
I am alone and miserable; man will not associate with me; but one as deformed and horrible as myself would not deny herself to me. My companion must be of the same species and have the same defects. This being you must create.

Victor recoils.

VICTOR
I do refuse it, and no torture shall ever extort consent from me. You may render me the most miserable of men, but you shall never make me base in my own eyes.

THE CREATURE
You are in the wrong, and instead of threatening, I am content to reason with you. I am malicious because I am miserable. Am I not shunned and hated by all mankind? You, my creator, would tear me to pieces and triumph. Shall I respect man when he condemns me? Let him live with me in the interchange of kindness, and instead of injury I would bestow every benefit upon him. But that cannot be; the human senses are insurmountable barriers to our union. Yet mine shall not be the submission of abject slavery. If I cannot inspire love, I will cause fear, and chiefly towards you my arch-enemy. Yet mine shall not be the submission of abject slavery. I will revenge my injuries; if I cannot inspire love, I will cause fear. I will work at your destruction, nor finish until I desolate your heart, so that you shall curse the hour of your birth.

Victor is torn—horror, pity, dread.

THE CREATURE (CONT'D)
What I ask of you is reasonable and moderate; I demand a creature of another sex, but as hideous as myself. It is true, we shall be monsters, cut off from all the world; but on that account we shall be more attached to one another. Our lives will not be happy, but they will be harmless and free from the misery I now feel. Oh! My creator, make me happy; let me feel gratitude towards you for one benefit! Let me see that I excite the sympathy of some existing thing; do not deny me my request!

VICTOR
You propose to fly from the habitations of man, to dwell in those wilds where the beasts of the field will be your only companions. How can you, who long for the love and sympathy of man, persevere in this exile? You will return and again seek their kindness, and you will meet with their detestation; your evil passions will be renewed, and you will then have a companion to aid you in the task of destruction.

THE CREATURE
I swear to you, by the earth which I inhabit, and by you that made me, that if you grant my prayer, while they exist you shall never behold me again. I will go to the vast wilds of South America. My food is not that of man; I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite; acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment. My companion will be of the same nature as myself and will be content with the same fare. We shall make our bed of dried leaves; the sun will shine on us as on man and will ripen our food. The picture I present to you is peaceful and human, and you must feel that you could deny it only in the wantonness of power and cruelty.

Long silence. Victor’s resolve cracks under the weight of the argument and the memory of the dead.

VICTOR
I consent to your demand, on your solemn oath to quit Europe forever, and every other place in the neighbourhood of man, as soon as I shall deliver into your hands a female who will accompany you in your exile.

THE CREATURE
I swear. I will watch your progress with unquiet eyes, and leave you in peace only when the work is complete. I shall be with you on your wedding-night.

The Creature departs over the ice with the speed of lightning. Victor is left alone in the hut as the sun sets behind the snowy precipices.

EXT. CHAMOUNIX AND GENEVA - DAY

Victor returns to his family, altered, silent. He cannot explain. Elizabeth watches him with loving dread. Alphonse urges marriage to steady him.

ALPHONSE FRANKENSTEIN
I confess, my son, that I have always looked forward to your marriage with our dear Elizabeth as the tie of our domestic comfort.

VICTOR
I will marry Elizabeth. When I return from a journey I must make—to England—I will be hers forever.

ELIZABETH
Go if you must. Only come back to us.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - DAY

Preparations. Clerval is to accompany Victor—delighted at the prospect of travel and learning. Victor’s true purpose is a secret hell.

EXT. RHINE AND ENGLISH COAST - DAY

Montage: boat on the Rhine; Clerval’s raptures at scenery and ruins; Victor’s face closed, watching every shadow. London. Scientific acquaintances. Materials gathered under pretence of study.

EXT. SCOTTISH HIGHLANDS - DAY

Bleak islands. Victor leaves Clerval in Scotland with excuses and takes a solitary residence on a remote Orkney isle—a miserable hut, sparsely peopled.

INT. ORKNEY HUT - WORKSHOP - NIGHT

A second filthy creation. Instruments. A half-formed female figure on the table. Victor works with loathing, not exaltation. His hands shake.

Through the window, on moonlit rocks, a vast silhouette watches—the Creature, waiting.

INT. ORKNEY HUT - WORKSHOP - NIGHT

Victor pauses over the unfinished female. Imagination shows him a race of devils; the female refusing the compact; two monsters loose upon the world.

He looks up. At the window—the Creature’s face, a ghastly grin.

In a frenzy Victor tears the half-finished creature to pieces. The work of months destroyed in moments.

Outside, a howl of rage. The Creature bursts into the hut.

THE CREATURE
Shall each man find a wife for his bosom, and each beast have his mate, and I be alone? I had feelings of affection, and they were requited by detestation and scorn. Man! You may hate, but beware! Your hours will pass in dread and misery, and soon the bolt will fall which must ravish from you your happiness forever. Remember, I shall be with you on your wedding-night.

VICTOR
Leave me! I have resolved. I will never create another like you, your wickedness equalled only by your deformity.

THE CREATURE
I go; but remember, I shall be with you on your wedding-night.

He vanishes into the dark.

EXT. ORKNEY SHORE - NIGHT

Victor packs the remains of the female into a basket, weights it, rows out alone upon a black sea, and sinks the basket far from land. He drifts, exhausted, and falls asleep in the boat.

EXT. IRISH COAST - DAY

A storm drives the boat ashore. Hostile faces. Fishermen seize him.

IRISH FISHERMAN
You must come to Mr. Kirwin. A murder has been done—a gentleman found strangled upon the beach. You were seen in a boat near this place.

INT. MR. KIRWIN'S HOUSE - IRELAND - DAY

MR. KIRWIN, a magistrate of mild manners, examines Victor. They lead him to view the body.

It is HENRY CLERVAL—black marks of fingers on his neck, the face Victor loved distorted in death.

Victor falls into a long, raving illness, accusing himself as the murderer of William, Justine, and Clerval.

INT. MR. KIRWIN'S HOUSE - IRELAND - DAY

Weeks later. Victor slowly recovers under Kirwin’s unexpected kindness. Alphonse arrives, aged almost beyond recognition, and takes his son in his arms.

ALPHONSE FRANKENSTEIN
My son—we will go home.

EXT. SEA VOYAGE TO GENEVA - DAY

Father and son on deck. Victor is a shadow. Alphonse tries to speak of Elizabeth, of hope. Victor hears only the Creature’s promise.

VICTOR (V.O.)
I shall be with you on your wedding-night. I thought the threat applied to my own life—that I would die, and Elizabeth be free of my curse. I was blind.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - DAY

Home. Elizabeth greets them with tears of joy and fear. The house is quieter without William, without Justine, without Henry’s letters.

ELIZABETH
Something whispers to me not to depend too much on the prospect that is opened before us—but I will not listen. We have been too long unhappy.

VICTOR
I am the cause of this—I alone. If I survive this night, Elizabeth, I will confide to you a dreadful secret.

She searches his face and does not press him.

INT. CHURCH - GENEVA - DAY

A quiet wedding. Victor and Elizabeth joined. His eyes continually seek the doors, the windows, every shadow. Alphonse blesses them with faltering voice.

EXT. LAKE GENEVA - EVENING

They embark for a family villa at Evian for the wedding night. Fair wind. Mountains darkening. Victor armed, restless, scanning the shores.

INT. VILLA AT EVIAN - BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

Elizabeth retires to the chamber. Victor paces the outer rooms and passages, pistol in hand, determined to meet his enemy alone.

A dreadful scream from the bedroom.

Victor rushes in.

Elizabeth lies flung across the bed, murdered—the murderous mark of the fiend’s grasp on her neck. Her golden hair spilled. Her face half-covered.

At the open window, for an instant, the Creature’s grinning face in a flash of lightning—then gone into the night.

Victor fires into the dark. Emptiness. He falls upon Elizabeth’s body in helpless agony.

EXT. VILLA AT EVIAN - NIGHT

Servants and neighbors gather. Victor is carried in a fever of grief. The lake and mountains give no answer.

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - DAY

Alphonse, struck by this last blow, sinks rapidly. Victor kneels by his father’s bed.

ALPHONSE FRANKENSTEIN
Elizabeth—William—

He dies in Victor’s arms. The house is a tomb.

INT. CEMETERY - GENEVA - NIGHT

Victor at the family graves—Caroline, William, and now Alphonse and the memory of Elizabeth and Henry. Rain. He kneels in the mud and swears aloud.

VICTOR
I devote myself, either in my life or death, to his destruction. I call on you, spirits of the dead, and on you, wandering ministers of vengeance, to aid and conduct me in my work. Let the cursed and hellish monster drink deep of agony; let him feel the despair that now torments me.

A grim laugh answers from the darkness among the tombs—the Creature.

THE CREATURE
I am satisfied, miserable wretch! You have determined to live, and I am satisfied.

Victor springs up, but the Creature is already fled.

EXT. EUROPEAN WASTES AND RUSSIAN STEPPES - DAY

Pursuit. Months and years compress into a relentless chase: Victor following traces—barked trees, scraps of food, taunting messages carved in bark or left on stone.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
My reign is not yet over—you live, and my power is complete. Follow me; I seek the everlasting ices of the north, where you will feel the misery of cold and frost, to which I am impassive.

Victor buys a sledge, dogs, supplies. The trail leads ever north, into the Arctic.

EXT. ARCTIC ICE - DAY

Victor’s sledge races over the pack. Dogs drop and die. He presses on, gaunt, frozen, unkillable by anything but the end of his purpose.

In the distance—the Creature’s sledge, always ahead, always just in reach.

A break in the ice. Victor’s sledge is destroyed. He is cast adrift on a shrinking floe—until Walton’s ship appears in the fog.

INT. WALTON'S CABIN - NIGHT

Back to the frame. Victor finishes his tale, spent. Walton sits in silence, the pen idle at last.

VICTOR
That is my story, miserable and imperfect as it is. When I would explain the purpose for which I had journeyed so far, my voice failed me. Walton—if you should ever come upon him—swear that he shall not escape; thrust your sword into his heart. I will hover near and direct the steel aright.

ROBERT WALTON
I have longed for a friend. I have found one only to lose him to this despair. Would that I could heal you—

VICTOR
My fate is nearly fulfilled. I wait but for one event, and then I shall repose in peace.

EXT. ARCTIC SEA - PACK ICE - DAY

The ice closes harder about the ship. The crew, led by Willoughby’s anxious courage and Fletcher’s quiet concern, beg Walton to turn south when the floes open.

LIEUTENANT WILLOUGHBY
Sir—the men will not perish for glory. When the passage clears, we must return.

Walton’s face is torn between the pole and the living.

INT. WALTON'S CABIN - DAY

Victor, hearing the mutiny of necessity, rises from his berth with a last strength.

VICTOR
What do you mean? What do you demand of your captain? Are you, then, so easily turned from your design? Did you not call this a glorious expedition? You were hereafter to be hailed as the benefactors of your species. And now—behold! You are opposing yourselves to your own wills. Be men, or be more than men. Do not return to your families with the stigma of disgrace marked on your brows. Return as heroes who have fought and conquered, and who know not what it is to turn their backs on the foe.

The men are moved—but the ice and death are real. Walton yields.

ROBERT WALTON
I will not lead you to death. When the ice frees us, we steer for England.

Victor sinks back, the last fire dying in him.

INT. WALTON'S CABIN - NIGHT

Victor calls Walton close. His voice is nearly gone.

VICTOR
Farewell, Walton! Seek happiness in tranquillity and avoid ambition, even if it be only the apparently innocent one of distinguishing yourself in science and discoveries. Yet why do I say this? I have myself been blasted in these hopes, yet another may succeed.

His eyes close. A last breath. Victor Frankenstein dies.

Walton weeps over the body of his friend.

INT. WALTON'S CABIN - NIGHT

Later. A sound at the cabin window. Walton turns.

THE CREATURE stands over Victor’s body—gigantic, weather-scarred, grief and rage contorted on the yellow face. He looks upon his creator with a mixture of anguish and self-loathing.

Walton reaches for a weapon. The Creature does not attack.

THE CREATURE
That is also my victim. In his murder my crimes are consummated; the miserable series of my being is wound to its close! Oh, Frankenstein! Generous and self-devoted being! What does it avail that I now ask thee to pardon me? I, who irretrievably destroyed thee by destroying all thou lovedst.

ROBERT WALTON
It is not pity that you feel; you lament only because the victim of your malignity is withdrawn from your power.

THE CREATURE
Oh, it is not thus—not thus. Yet such must be the impression conveyed to you by what appears to be the purport of my actions. Yet I seek not a fellow feeling in my misery. No sympathy may I ever find. When I first sought it, it was the love of virtue, the feelings of happiness and affection with which my whole being overflowed, that I wished to be participated. But now crime has degraded me beneath the meanest animal. No guilt, no mischief, no malignity, no misery, can be found comparable to mine. When I run over the frightful catalogue of my sins, I cannot believe that I am the same creature whose thoughts were once filled with sublime and transcendent visions of the beauty and the majesty of goodness. But it is even so; the fallen angel becomes a malignant devil. Yet even that enemy of God and man had friends and associates in his desolation; I am alone.

He gazes again at Victor.

THE CREATURE (CONT'D)
I shall quit your vessel on the ice raft which brought me hither and shall seek the most northern extremity of the globe; I shall collect my funeral pile and consume to ashes this miserable frame, that its remains may afford no light to any curious and unhallowed wretch who would create such another as I have been. I shall die. I shall no longer feel the agonies which now consume me or be the prey of feelings unsatisfied, yet unquenched.

He turns to the window, then back once more.

THE CREATURE (CONT'D)
Farewell! I leave you, and in you the last of humankind whom these eyes will ever behold. Farewell, Frankenstein! If thou wert yet alive and yet cherished a desire of revenge against me, it would be better satiated in my life than in my destruction. But it was not so; thou didst seek my extinction, that I might not cause greater wretchedness; and if yet, in some mode unknown to me, thou hadst not ceased to think and feel, thou wouldst not desire against me a vengeance greater than that which I feel. Blasted as thou wert, my agony was still superior to thine, for the bitter sting of remorse will not cease to rankle in my wounds until death shall close them forever.

He springs from the cabin window to the hanging ice raft below.

EXT. ARCTIC SEA - PACK ICE - NIGHT

The Creature is borne away on the ice, across the waves, lost in darkness and distance—toward the northern extremity and the funeral fire he has promised.

Walton stands at the rail a long time, then turns the ship’s course, when the ice permits, toward home.

FADE OUT.

THE END
